{
  "text": "At 30 dpi, pDCs and NK cells were 7-fold and .2-fold more infectious than lymphocytes, respectively (Table 3 and Figure S2 ). In agreement with other reports [CITATION_1] PrP c expression was undetectable in pDCs ( Figure S3 ). Although prion replicationcompetence of cells cannot be predicted solely on the basis of PrP c expression levels [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , pDCs seemed a priori a poor candidate for a role in prion replication. However, that pDCs are instead highly infectious, as shown in this study, underscores the importance of prion sequestration and dissemination by antigenpresenting cells. PDCs are natural type 1 IFN-producing cells, located in the T cell rich periarteriolar lymphoid sheath of lymphoid organs. Their distribution differs from conventional DCs which are predominantly found in the marginal zone and outer PALS, but not in the red pulp of the spleen [CITATION_4] . Interestingly, in a steady state, NK cells are also found in areas of antigen entry to lymphoid organs, in perifollicular regions, in the paracortex, and especially in the medulla zone within lymphatic sinuses [CITATION_5] . Whether the distribution of pDCs and NK cells in lymphoid organs is related to their high prion titers has to be further investigated. A bidirectional cross-talk between DCs and NK cells has recently been shown to play a key role in host defense [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In contrast to highly infected pDCs, macrophages showed about eight fold lower prion titers. Of note, the in vivo depletion of macrophages shortened scrapie incubation times [CITATION_8] , suggesting that macrophages have a protective role on disease progression.",
  "correct_citation": {
